Well use data on housing values in suburbs of Boston. They are in an R package called MASS. (An R package is a collection of code, data, and documentation. MASS refers to the book Modern Applied Statistics with S. R developed from the earlier language, S.) The MASS package comes with the default R installation, so its already on your computer. However, its not loaded into your R session by default. So well load it via the require() command (theres nothing for you to do here):

require("MASS")
## Loading required package: MASS

Run ?Boston (outside this R Markdown document) to read the help page for the Boston data frame.

Convert the chas variable to a factor with labels off and on (referring to the Charles river).

bos <- Boston
bos$chas <- factor(bos$chas, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("off", "on"))

How many rows are in the Boston data frame? How many columns?

rows <- nrow(Boston)

What does a row represent? A row represents a neighborhood

What does a column represent? A column represents a variable for every neighborhood which would later be used to predict the median value (last column) of the house of interest.

Make a density plot (with rug) of tax rates.

plot(density(bos$tax), main = paste0("Density of Neighborhood Tax Rates"), xlab = "Tax Rate per $10000")
rug(bos$tax)

Describe the shape of the distribution of tax rates. The distribution is binomial.

Note that the distribution shape doesnt make sense in light of the rug representation of the data. Make a histogram of the tax rates.

hist(bos$tax, main = paste0("Histogram of Neighborhood Tax Rate"), xlab = "Tax Rate per $10000")

Why is the second peak of the density plot so large? In what way is the rug representation of the data inadequate? Write a line or two of code to figure it out, and then explain it.

tax.table <- table(bos$tax)
tax.table[names(tax.table) > 600]
## 
## 666 711 
## 132   5

The second peak in the density plot is large because there are 132 neighborhoods that have the same tax rate higher than 600. This might because after a certain value of income, the tax rate became fixed, so that rug is also inadequate because it fails to show the amount of houses that share this exactly same rate.

Look into the highest-crime neighborhood by making a single graph of one column of three rows:

  • Find the row number, r, of the neighborhood with the highest crim.
  • Make a density plot of crim. Include a rug to show the data.
  • Add a red circle at (x, y) = (max crime rate, 0) to make this maximum crime rate stand out.
  • Make a density plot with rug of medv, adding a red circle at (x, y) = (medv[r], 0) to see what medv corresponds to the highest crime rate.
  • Repeat the last step for ptratio.
b1 = bos[which.max(bos$crim),]
# r = 381
layout(matrix(c(1,2,3), nrow = 3, ncol = 1))
plot(density(bos$crim), main = paste0("Density of per capita crime rate by town"))
rug(bos$crim)
points(bos$crim[which.max(bos$crim)], 0, col = "red", pch = 19)
plot(density(bos$medv), main = paste0("Density of Median Value of Owner Occupied Homes in $1000s"))
rug(bos$medv)
points(bos$medv[which.max(bos$crim)], 0, col = "red", pch = 19)
plot(density(bos$ptratio), main = paste0("Density of Pupil-teacher Ratio by Town"))
rug(bos$ptratio)
points(bos$ptratio[which.max(bos$crim)], 0, col = "red", pch = 19)

What do you notice about the ptratio and medv for the highest-crime neighborhood?

The neighborhood that has the highest-crime rate has a very large pupil to teacher ratios and a very low median value of owner occupied homes.
